<paragraph id="8BC3369BB737966E21B6CE69FF62B920" blockId="0.[151,1437,1749,2026]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1437,151,717]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="576" pageId="0" pageNumber="575">
<emphasis id="B908EA89B737966F21B6CE69FE4BBF56" bold="true" box="[199,463,1821,1846]" pageId="0" pageNumber="575">
<typeStatus id="54C78839B737966F21B6CE69FEB0BF56" box="[199,308,1821,1846]" pageId="0" pageNumber="575">Holotype</typeStatus>
description.
</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity id="4C849B7EB737966F234ACE69FD1FBF55" box="[571,667,1821,1846]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.8" pageId="0" pageNumber="575" unit="mm" value="6.8">6.8 mm</quantity>
. Entirely metallic green. 
<emphasis id="B908EA89B737966F22A0CE69FB9EBF56" bold="true" box="[977,1050,1821,1846]" pageId="0" pageNumber="575">Head:</emphasis>
frons glabrous with punctiform sculpture. Clypeus without transverse carina. Antennae black, serrate from fourth article. 
<emphasis id="B908EA89B737966F25E1CE35FA8DBF3A" bold="true" box="[1168,1289,1857,1882]" pageId="0" pageNumber="575">Pronotum</emphasis>
depressed at the sides, wider in middle, with posterior angles obtuse. White pubescence few visible at the anterior angles. Superficial and transverse sculpture, dotted with small punctures. Premarginal carinula interrupted, not entire. Marginal carinae joined at the base. Mentonniere with anterior margin slightly sinuate in middle. Prosternal plate wide and parallel. 
<emphasis id="B908EA89B737966F2017CEA5FE5ABF8A" bold="true" box="[358,478,2001,2026]" pageId="0" pageNumber="575">Scutellum</emphasis>
with transverse carina absent, replaced by a thick callus. 
<emphasis id="B908EA89B737966F2515CEA5FB35BF8A" bold="true" box="[1124,1201,2001,2026]" pageId="0" pageNumber="575">Elytra</emphasis>
rounded at the apex, with coarse and sparse denticulation; disc with 
<number id="3DB424BCB736966E23DAC9ECFD3DB8D0" box="[683,697,152,176]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" value="4.0">4</number>
(
<number id="3DB424BCB736966E23B8C9ECFD5CB8D0" box="[713,728,152,176]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number id="3DB424BCB736966E2399C9ECFD73B8D0" box="[744,759,152,176]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" value="2.0">2</number>
) slightly visible spots of white pubescence along the suture: the first pair at of the length, the second at the apex. 
<emphasis id="B908EA89B736966E2397C9C8FCE5B8B5" bold="true" box="[742,865,188,213]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">Underside</emphasis>
with two white spots of pubescence at the sides of ventrites 
<number id="3DB424BCB736966E2070C994FE8BB898" box="[257,271,224,248]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" value="2.0">2</number>
and 
<number id="3DB424BCB736966E203BC994FEDEB898" box="[330,346,224,248]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" value="3.0">3</number>
. One white spot also at the base of the first laterotergum. 
<emphasis id="B908EA89B736966E228EC9ABFBB3B898" bold="true" box="[1023,1079,223,248]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">Legs</emphasis>
with all claws simply toothed; metatarsus shorter than the metafemur. Basal metatarsomere little longer than the second (
<number id="3DB424BCB736966E25FDC870FB12B97C" box="[1164,1174,260,284]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" value="1.0">1</number>
&lt;
<number id="3DB424BCB736966E25D8C870FB3DB97C" box="[1193,1209,260,284]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number id="3DB424BCB736966E25BAC870FB5DB97C" box="[1227,1241,260,284]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" value="3.0">3</number>
). 
<emphasis id="B908EA89B736966E259CC870FAE5B97D" bold="true" box="[1261,1377,260,285]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">Aedeagus</emphasis>
as in fig. 
<number id="3DB424BCB736966E21B5C85CFF54B920" box="[196,208,296,320]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" value="1.0">1</number>
c.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3666510B736966E21B6C838FB15B9CD" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC3369BB736966E21B6C838FB15B9CD" blockId="1.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">
<emphasis id="B908EA89B736966E21B6C838FEBFB905" bold="true" box="[199,315,332,357]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">Variation.</emphasis>
<typeStatus id="54C78839B736966E2037C839FE37B905" box="[326,435,333,357]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">Paratypes</typeStatus>
range in length from 
<quantity id="4C849B7EB736966E23D8C838FCCEB904" box="[681,842,332,357]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.2" metricValueMax="7.9" metricValueMin="6.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" unit="mm" value="7.2" valueMax="7.9" valueMin="6.5">6.5 to 7.9 mm</quantity>
. Two specimens have the elytral pubescent spots not visible. Two males have the frons dark green, almost black. The only apparent secondary sexual character is in the color of the frons of the females being golden, though one has a green frons like the males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3666510B736966E21B6C8C3FADAB9B0" box="[199,1374,439,464]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BC3369BB736966E21B6C8C3FADAB9B0" blockId="1.[151,1437,151,717]" box="[199,1374,439,464]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">
<emphasis id="B908EA89B736966E21B6C8C3FECAB9B0" bold="true" box="[199,334,439,464]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">Etymology.</emphasis>
I name this beetle after my friend and colleague Thibaut Delsinne, discoverer of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3666510B736966E21B6C8A8FBA7BAAD" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC3369BB736966E21B6C8A8FBA7BAAD" blockId="1.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">
<emphasis id="B908EA89B736966E21B6C8A8FECBB995" bold="true" box="[199,335,476,501]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">Comments.</emphasis>
All specimens were found on the foliage of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D18B736966E22F3C8A9FAFAB994" authority="(Ruiz &amp; Pav.) Ewan" authorityName="(Ruiz &amp; Pav.) Ewan" box="[898,1406,476,501]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gentianaceae" genus="Macrocarpaea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ovalis">
<emphasis id="B908EA89B736966E22F3C8A9FBFDB994" box="[898,1145,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">Macrocarpaea ovalis</emphasis>
(Ruiz &amp; Pav.) Ewan
</taxonomicName>
= 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D18B736966E21E6CB75FD82BA78" authority="Gilg" authorityName="Gilg" box="[151,518,511,536]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gentianaceae" genus="Macrocarpaea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arborescens">
<emphasis id="B908EA89B736966E21E6CB75FE48BA78" box="[151,460,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">Macrocarpaea arborescens</emphasis>
Gilg
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D18B736966E2364C88BFD34BA78" box="[533,688,511,536]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gentianaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Gentianaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation id="13472A1EB736966E23B6C88BFC8FBA78" box="[711,779,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1970,1992]" captionTargetBox="[215,1364,704,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[215,1364,195,1931]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Cajanuma: biotope of Agrilus delsinnei n. sp. In the foreground Macrocarpaea ovalis (Ruiz &amp; Pav.) Ewan (photo T. Delsinne)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245056/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">
Fig. 
<number id="3DB424BCB736966E238DC88BFC8FBA78" box="[764,779,511,536]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
), where they had found refuge from adverse weather. The fact that all the specimens were found on the same species of plant suggests that this may be the larval host. The altitude where the specimens were found shows the great climatic adaptability of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D18B736966E2599CB3CFABEBA00" box="[1256,1338,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B908EA89B736966E2599CB3CFABEBA00" box="[1256,1338,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">Agrilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. To my knowledge, however, the record in height for South 
<collectingCountry id="F36B760BB736966E2275CB18FCE0BAE5" box="[772,868,620,645]" name="United States of America" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">America</collectingCountry>
belongs to a species in 
<collectingCountry id="F36B760BB736966E25FACB18FB66BAE5" box="[1163,1250,620,645]" name="Bolivia" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
: 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D18B736966E2580CB18FEB3BAC8" authority="Curletti, 2015" authorityName="Curletti" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="altitudinalis">
<emphasis id="B908EA89B736966E2580CB18FA1FBAE4" box="[1265,1435,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">A. altitudinalis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B6AB736966E21E6CBFBFEB3BAC8" author="Curletti" box="[151,311,655,680]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" refString="Curletti, G. (2015) Three new species of Agrilini (Coleoptera Buprestidae) from Argentina and Bolivia. Giornale italiano di Entomologia, 14 (60), 25 - 30." type="journal article" year="2015">
Curletti, 
<number id="3DB424BCB736966E218ECBFBFEB3BAC8" box="[255,311,655,680]" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" value="2015.0">2015</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
that was found at 
<quantity id="4C849B7EB736966E236CCBE4FD05BAC7" box="[541,641,656,680]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" unit="m" value="3800.0">3,800 m</quantity>
. Among the South American species that have a similar pattern of pubescent spots, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D18B736966E2024CBC0FE5DBAAC" box="[341,473,692,716]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="576" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delsinnei">
<emphasis id="B908EA89B736966E2024CBC0FE5DBAAC" box="[341,473,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="576">A. delsinnei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only one known without a carinate scutellum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
